\begin_layout Chapter
The Field & Where to Be
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Field Anatomy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Most marching that happens while being a member of the band will occur on
 a football field.
 This chapter will demonstrate how to understand the field to be most familiar
 with it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Terminology and Layout
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace defskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
The standard high school football field can be described using some vocabulary
 (a labeled football field is demonstrated in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand vref
reference "fig:field"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Field A rectangular section of ground dedicated to playing football.
 But in our case, it's for marching!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Yard
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

line A physical, vertical line that runs across the entire height of the
 field.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Hash A horizontal line that runs across the entire width of the field, dividing
 the field into thirds.
 The 
\series bold
home hash 
\series default
is closest to the home sideline, and the 
\series bold
away/visitor hash 
\series default
is closest to the away sideline.
 There are physical, small, horizontal sections of this line where the hash
 meets the yard line (see Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:field-markings"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Sideline A physical, horizontal line that runs across the entire width of
 the field, defining the upper and lower edges of the field.
 The sideline next to the press box or tower is the 
\series bold
home sideline
\series default
; the sideline on the opposite side of the field is the 
\series bold
away/visitor sideline
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
End
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

zone A physical, vertical line that runs across the entire height of the
 field, defining the left and right edges of the field.
 When facing the press box from the field, the right and left end zones
 are defined by the right and left sides of the person.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
If the home sideline is north, then the right end zone is east and the left
 end zone is west.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Tick A mark on the practice field, usually orange, spaced 90 inches apart
 spanning the height of each yard line.
 These marks are only found on the practice field for reference.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The football field is 100 yards across and 52.5 yards tall.
 It is divided by 15 yard lines starting from the left end zone and moving
 towards the right end zone.
 Each yard line has a distance of 5 yards in between.
 Every other yard line is labeled by its distance from the nearest end zone
 (e.g., 10 yards, 20 yards, etc.).
 The middle yard line is marked 50 yards.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The football field is divided into three sections vertically, making three
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

rows,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 divided by the hashes.
 The home hash sits 17.5 yards south from the home sideline.
 The away side line is 17.5 yards north of the away sideline, effectively
 making the distance in between hashes also 17.5 yards.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The term 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

back field
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 refers to the part of the field closest to the away sideline (typically
 between the away sideline and away hash).
 Although the term 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

front field
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 can refer the the part of the field closest to the home sideline, it is
 not used as often.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The part of the field in between the left sideline and the 50 yard line
 is called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

field left.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 The part of the field in between the right sideline and the 50 yard line
 is called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

field right.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename graphics/field.svg
	width 100text%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:field"

\end_inset

A standard football field.
 The grid represents 4 8:5 steps.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Markings
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The field is marked in several ways to help performers find their location
 on the field (a diagram is available in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand vref
reference "fig:field-markings"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The yard lines and end zones are marked by solid, white, vertical lines
 spanning the entire height of the field.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The sidelines are marked by solid, white horizontal lines spanning the entire
 width of the field.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Every 90 inches (7.5 ft), starting from the sidelines, (4 * 8:5 steps, see
 Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand vref
reference "step-size"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for details), a short, horizontal, orange 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

tick mark
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is drawn.
 These lines represent 4 even 8:5 steps.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In lieu of an orange tick mark at the hashes, a short, horizontal 
\emph on
white 
\emph default

\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

tick mark
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is drawn.
 These are 630 inches (52.5 ft) from each sideline.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It should be noted that 
\emph on
only on the practice field will orange ticks be available for reference
\emph default
.
 Actual performance fields (e.g., Jamie Jent Stadium, etc.) do not have orange
 ticks, although all other markings are present.
 So, it is important to use the orange ticks when learning, but you must
 be comfortable without them too!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename graphics/field_markings.svg
	lyxscale 200
	scale 150

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:field-markings"

\end_inset

A small section of the practice football field, with the markings displayed.
 Gray lines represent orange tick marks.
 Solid ticks represent hash lines.
 Solid horizontal line represents sideline.
 Solid vertical lines represent yard lines.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Interpreting Your Dotsheet
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\noun on
Dotsheet
\noun default
 is a personalized slip of paper that defines where you are in each set
 of the show.
 Each performer will get a unique dotsheet.
 This section will demonstrate the terminology, abbreviations, and some
 examples of interpreting the sheet.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Terminology
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Show The performance that you will be presenting this year!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Drill A show consists of drills.
 Usually each song in the show correlates to each drill.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Set A specific point in time in the show that defines where each performer
 is.
 A show can consist of many sets, usually close 20.
 You will have to know where you need to be for each set!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Coordinate/Dot The specific 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

x/y
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 location that the performer is to be at in a set.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Form A loose term to define a group of performers on the field.
 Forms can last throughout the whole show, or may only last for a set.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Dotsheet Layout
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\align left
