\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\align left
The dotsheet consists of four columns:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Set — The current set number.
 A set can also have subsets (#15A is a subset of #15).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Move — The amount of beats that elapse since the last set.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Right-Left — The X coordinate of the performer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Visitor-Home — The Y coordinate of the performer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The right-left and visitor-home columns use a special type of notation to
 define distance.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The format for right-left notation: 
\series bold
[On 50 yd ln/[left/right]: [(x) steps [inside/outside] of/on] (x) yd ln]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The format for visitor-home notation: 
\series bold
[On home sideline/On home hash/On visitor hash/On visitor sideline/(x) steps
 [in front of/behind] [Home sideline/Home hash/Visitor hash/Visitor Sideline]]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here are some examples of right-left notation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If the coordinate was 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Right: 2 steps inside of 40 yd ln
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 find the right 40 yard line, and take two 8:5 steps towards the 50 yard
 line.
 This is the X-coordinate of the set.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If the coordinate was 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Right: 3 steps outside of 25 yd ln
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 find the right 25 yard line, and take three 8:5 steps away from the 50
 yard line.
 This is the X-coordinate of the set.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If the coordinate was 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Left: 2.5 steps inside of 35 yd ln
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 find the left 35 yard line, and take two and a half 8:5 steps towards the
 50 yard line.
 This is the X-coordinate of the set.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If the coordinate was 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Left: 3.75 steps outside of 45 yd ln
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 find the left 45 yard line, and take three and three-quarters 8:5 steps
 away the 50 yard line.
 This is the X-coordinate of the set.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If the coordinate was 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

On 50 yd ln
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 find the 50 yard line.
 That was easy!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here are some examples of visitor-home notation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If the coordinate was 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

5.0 stps behind Home hash
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, find the home hash, and take five steps away from the press box/tower.
 This is the Y-coordinate of the set.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If the coordinate was 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

0.25 stps in frnt of Visitor hash
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, find the visitor hash, and take a quarter step towards the press box/tower.
 This is the Y-coordinate of the set.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If the coordinate was 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

2 stps behind of home sideline
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, find the home sideline, and take two steps away from the press box/tower.
 This is the Y-coordinate of the set.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If the coordinate was 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

On visitor sideline
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, find the visitor sideline.
 That was easy!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Fundamentals
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "chap:Fundamentals"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this main part of the book, each fundamental, in ideal chronological
 teaching order, is presented in full detail.
 Before we begin, I want to provide a definition for 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

fundamental
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

marching maneuver
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and how they differ:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Fundamental A skill demonstrated on the marching field that is used in more
 complex maneuvers and is generally found commonly in a marching show.
 For example, every marching show will (hopefully) include 
\emph on
Attention, Roll Step, 
\emph default
and 
\emph on
Mark Time
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Marching
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

maneuver A set of fundamentals applied together to achieve a visual or audible
 effect on the field.
 For example, 2017's 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

The Not So Little Baby Show
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 included 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

diamond cutters
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 which took advantage of several fundamentals.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This book will focus more on fundamentals than marching maneuvers, since
 they are more common and can apply to most all marching shows.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Basics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These are the most rudimentary fundamentals that the band should absolutely
 be comfortable with and can execute with perfection.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Attention
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\noun on
Attention
\noun default
 is the most rudimentary fundamental of any, since the band will be holding
 this position for the majority of the time.
 Therefore it is most absolutely necessary the band can do this perfectly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The goal of 
\emph on
holding Attention
\emph default
 is to allow the band to appear uniform when arranged together, whether
 it is on the practice field practicing fundamentals, on the field marching
 a show, walking at an 
\emph on
Attention Walk
\emph default
, or marching in 
\emph on
Parade Block
\emph default
.
 When the band is not uniform, it is simply unappealing to look at; noticing
 a person swaying side to side, itching their leg with their foot, or looking
 around, can break the aesthetic of a marching band.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is also important to realize the word choice of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

attention.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 If you are holding Attention, you are also 
\emph on
paying attention
\emph default
! If a leader gives you a command while you are holding Attention and you
 fail to respond to the command, we've broken the purpose of Attention!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All commands and instructions will be performed when the band is holding
 Attention.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Attention pose
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These descriptors demonstrate Attention with no horn for the standard wind
 player (the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

imaginary trumpet
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Attention).
 This pose is demonstrated in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand vref
reference "fig:attention"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Feet placed side by side, toes and heels together, toes pointing forwards.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Legs slightly bent, just enough that knees are not locked, pointing forwards.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Hips level and providing even weight distribution to both legs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Torso straight and tall, core engaged.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Shoulders relaxed, but back, square, and even.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Arms extended forwards, elbows pointing out and down, relaxed, forming a
 90º angle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Hands right hand forms a fist, right thumb resting on tops of index and
 middle fingers, left hand wrapping around, left thumb resting on top of
 fist, at eye level.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Head looking slightly up at 15º angle, neck relaxed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename pose_graphics/attention/attention_front.svg
	lyxscale 10
	scale 10

\end_inset


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename pose_graphics/attention/attention_side.svg
	lyxscale 10
	scale 10

\end_inset


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename pose_graphics/attention/attention_hands.svg
	lyxscale 10
	scale 10

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:attention"

\end_inset

The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

imaginary trumpet
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Attention pose.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
For each instrument:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
Flute/Piccolo/Clarinet The horn should be held vertically, with the hands
 positioned in normal playing position, arms extended outwards.
 The mouthpiece should be just above eye level.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
Saxophones The saxophone should be positioned horizontally, resting on the
 stomach with the help of the neck strap.
 The hands should be placed in normal playing position.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
Trumpets/Mellophones/Trombones The horn should be held vertically with the
 bell facing down, close to eye level, with hands positioned in normal playing
 position.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
Baritone The baritone should be held with the right arm, holding against
 the torso, bell facing forwards.
 The left arm should be down, relaxed, but in place and holding a fist.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
Sousaphone The sousaphone should be appropriately worn, with the neck and
 mouthpiece angled down.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
Snare/Tenor
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Drum The sticks should be held together in opposing directions, with the
 right hand stick closest to the body.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
Bass
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Drum The mallets should be held against the rim of the drum on the side
 closest to the body.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
Flag The flag should be held with the left hand near eye level, grabbing
 the cloth of the flag and holding it to the rod.
 The right hand should hold the rod near waist level.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Important aspects of Attention:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This position should be comfortable and easy to pose.
 If you are experiencing exhaustion, relax your shoulders, unlock your knees,
 and keep your weight distribution even between both legs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
When holding the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

imaginary trumpet
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or other instrument that requires you to hold your instrument out in front
 of you (all except saxophones, baritones, sousaphones, drum line, and color
 guard), do not tuck your elbows.
 If you were to draw a line from your wrists down to your elbows and extend
 that line outwards, it should hit the ground away from you, on either side.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Absolutely NO TALKING.
 How can you pay attention to your leader if you are talking to the people
 around you? The main point of not talking is to maintain a mental attention
 to the leader.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Tips for learning how to hold a good Attention:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
To know if you are holding your arms out far enough, check to see if someone
 can easily 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

sneak in for a hug.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 You are not holding a proper Attention if your arms are too extended or
 not extended enough.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
To know if you are holding your head at the correct angle, place your hand
 in an 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

L shape.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Place your index finger under the bottom of your chin and your thumb in
 between your clavicles.
 You can also imagine pointing your head to the tops of the trees.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
I can't recommend using the tree method, since your distance to a tree can
 affect the angle, and you probably won't have a tree to reference when
 you are marching a show on the field.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If you imagine your hips are a bucket of water that is 99% full, and you
 don't want to spill any water, you must keep your hips level to do so.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Imagine you are being pulled from the top of your head by a string, extending
 your spine all the way and up onto your toes.
 Hold this position, then 
\emph on
only
\emph default
 move your ankles so your feet are now flat on the ground.
 This should show how your back and torso should be positioned to maintain
 a good posture.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Falling into Attention
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

fall into Attention
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 means to begin holding the Attention pose and be ready for instructions.
 The band can either fall in synchronously or asynchronously (all at the
 same time or all at different times).
 Attention is the only command that can be called when the band is not in
 form.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Synchronously
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The band shall immediately fall into Attention when a leader shouts: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
BAN 'TEN HUT!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The timing of the syllables forms three even quarter notes of a 4/4 measure,
 landing on beats 1–3.
 The band shall then respond and fall into the Attention pose and await
 further commands:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
HUN!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The band's response shall land on beat 4 of the measure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Flex LilyPond
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

rhythm = 
\backslash
relative c'' {
\backslash
time 4/4
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
override NoteHead.style = #'cross
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

b4-.
 f-- b-.
 b}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

lyr = 
\backslash
lyricmode { BAN 'TEN HUT! 
\backslash
markup {
\backslash
bold HUN!}}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

<<   
\backslash
new Voice = melody 
\backslash
rhythm   
\backslash
new Lyrics 
\backslash
lyricsto melody 
\backslash
lyr >>
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Asynchronously
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The band shall, as quickly as possible, fall into Attention when a leader
 states one the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
Fall into Attention!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
Fall in!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The band does not provide a response when falling into Attention asynchronously.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Legal commands while at Attention
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Attention is the most basic state the band can be in, so any other command
 can be called while the band is at Attention.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Attention Walk
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the band can't be in step due to reasons, the band can 
\noun on
Attention Walk.
 
\noun default
To attention walk, simply walk at attention.
 This means every part of the body should appear to be holding Attention
 except for the legs.
 This also means the head should remain forward with the chin up, just as
 it is in Attention.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Parade Rest
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\noun on
Parade Rest 
\noun default
is the next most important fundamental to learn, since it is another basic
 pose that does not involve any movement and is often used next to Attention.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The goal of Parade Rest is to allow the band to remain uniform, while also
 resting.
 It requires less work to hold than Attention.
 Parade Rest is used commonly when the band is waiting for an event to happen,
 so that the band can return to Attention and continue marching.
 For example, while waiting for the clock to strike 00:00 for halftime,
 the band will hold Parade Rest to appear uniform while not specifically
 being in formation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Parade Rest pose
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These descriptors demonstrate Parade Rest with no horn for the standard
 wind player (the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

imaginary trumpet
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Parade Rest).
 This pose is demonstrated in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand vref
reference "fig:parade-rest"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Feet placed shoulder-width, or slightly greater, apart, toes pointing forwards.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Legs slightly bent, just enough that knees are not locked, pointing forwards.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Hips level and providing even weight distribution to both legs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Torso straight and tall, back straight, but relaxed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Shoulders relaxed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Arms left arm reaching behind back, right arm holding same pose as Attention.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Hands right hand maintains Attention pose.
 Left hand is placed in the small of the back, fingers straight and together,
 thumb resting next to index finger, hand horizontal to ground, horizontally
 centered in back.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
Head looking slightly up at 15º angle, neck relaxed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename pose_graphics/paraderest/paraderest_front.svg
	lyxscale 10
	scale 10

\end_inset


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename pose_graphics/paraderest/paraderest_side.svg
	lyxscale 10
	scale 10

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:parade-rest"

\end_inset

The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

imaginary trumpet
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Parade Rest pose.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

For each instrument:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
All
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

wind
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

instruments The left arm will follow the pose as defined previously.
 The right arm will maintain its instrument specific pose.
 The left foot will spread to be balanced shoulder-width apart.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
Drum
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

line The arms rest to the side holding the sticks, feet apart.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
Flag The flag is held parallel to the ground, feet apart.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Important aspects of Parade Rest:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This position should be comfortable and easy to pose.
 If you are experiencing exhaustion, relax your shoulders, unlock your knees,
 and keep your weight distribution even between both legs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The left hand should form a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

blade
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and be placed in the small of the back.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The right arm does not move.
 It does not come closer to the body.
 It should still be extended in the same manner as Attention.
 Just imagine your left arm is invisible, but still there to accompany the
 right arm.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Tips for learning how to hold a good Parade Rest:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
To find the perfect foot placement, position your feet so that they are
 directly underneath your armpits.
 This is an equivalent for those who spread too far when prompted on 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

shoulder-width.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Going in and out of Parade Rest
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The band 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

falls into
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Parade Rest asynchronously and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

moves to
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 Parade Rest synchronously.
 The band can only move to Parade Rest when at Attention and horns are down,
 or out-of-state.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Going in synchronously
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The band shall immediately move to Parade Rest when a leader shouts: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
BAN PA 'RADE HESS!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The timing of the syllables forms a dotted eighth, followed by a sixteenth,
 then two quarters.
 The band shall then respond and fall into the Parade Rest pose and await
 further commands:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
HUN!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The band's response shall land on beat 4 of the measure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Flex LilyPond
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

rhythm = 
\backslash
relative c'' {
\backslash
time 4/4
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
override NoteHead.style = #'cross
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

b8.-.
 b16 f4-- b4-.
 | b4}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

lyr = 
\backslash
lyricmode { BAN PA- RADE HESS! 
\backslash
markup {
\backslash
bold HUN!}}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

<<   
\backslash
new Voice = melody 
\backslash
rhythm   
\backslash
new Lyrics 
\backslash
lyricsto melody 
\backslash
lyr >>
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph
Transitioning
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To transition from Attention to Parade Rest, the left arm should quickly
 snap from its position in Attention to Parade Rest.
 The left foot should also move out the left, landing just under the armpit/shou
lder.
 The right foot never moves! By doing this, your center of mass will move
 to the left.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Falling in asynchronously
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The band shall, as quickly as possible, fall into Parade Rest when a leader
 states one the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
Fall into to Parade Rest!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If a whistle is blown with a long-short pattern, the band will fall to Parade
 Rest, although this may differ depending on context.
 If a whistle is blown, then falls in pitch, then rises back to the initial
 pitch, the band is expected to fall into Parade Rest.
 The band does not provide a response when falling into Parade Rest asynchronous
ly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Going out of Parade Rest
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is only one legal command the band can follow when holding Parade
 Rest: Attention.
 If any other command is given while the band is at Parade Rest, the band
 is expected to respond with:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
AS YOU WERE!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The timing of the syllables forms a dotted eighth, a sixteenth, followed
 by a quarter, starting on beat 4.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Flex LilyPond
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

<<   
\backslash
relative c''{
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
override NoteHead.style = #'cross
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
time 4/4
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

r2 r4 b8.
 f16 | b4
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
addlyrics { 
\backslash
markup 
\backslash
bold AS 
\backslash
markup 
\backslash
bold YOU 
\backslash
markup 
\backslash
bold WERE! } >>
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Horns Up/Down
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What is the point of a marching band if our instruments are always down?
 The band always puts its horns up and down together.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The horns up position
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When holding the imaginary trumpet, the only part of the body that moves
 is the arms and the hands.
 The hands are placed at or above eye level, while maintaining a 90º angle
 at the elbows.
 The hands bend slightly at the wrist so that the left thumb that is resting
 on the right fist is facing towards the face.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For each instrument:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
Flute The flute is held horizontally in a normal playing position.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
Clarinet The clarinet moves down (contrary to any other instrument) to reach
 the mouth for normal playing position.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
Saxophone The saxophone is lifted up vertically to a normal playing position.
 The neck strap should be adjusted to the saxophone 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

comes
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to the player, and not vice versa.
 The saxophone should be pushed forwards with the right hand to not rest
 against the stomach.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
Trumpet/Mellophone/Trombone The horn is rotated and lifted to come to a
 normal playing position.
 The angle of the horn should be ~15º above the horizon line.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
Baritone The baritone is grabbed with the left hand and brought up to a
 normal playing position.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
Sousaphone The neck and mouthpiece is rotated to come to the mouth of the
 performer for a normal playing position.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
Snare/Tenor
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Drum The sticks are held with appropriate grasp and point 45º inwards from
 center.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
Bass
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

Drum The mallets are extended outwards so the head of the mallets are positioned
 in the center of the drum head.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
Flag The flag is raised.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
add more here
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is important to note that for wind instruments, the mouthpiece of the
 instrument should not be in contact with the mouth; it only makes contact
 when playing.
 Trying to bring the horn up and directly into your mouth in a short, snappy
 move may not be good for the health of your mouth! 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Moving the horns
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The transition of moving the horn should be short and snappy.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Horns up
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The band will only transition to horns up from a command or a whistle pattern.
 The band will move to horns up if the following command is given:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
BAN HORNS UP!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The timing of the syllables forms three even quarter notes of a 4/4 measure,
 landing on beats 1–3.
 The band shall then respond and move to the horns up position:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
AND UP!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The timing of the syllables forms two even quarter notes, starting on beat
 4, landing on beat 1 of the next measure.
 The band will also move to horns up if three short whistles are given,
 indicating the beginning of a song.
 The band should respond with the previous response.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Flex LilyPond
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

rhythm = 
\backslash
relative c'' {
\backslash
time 4/4
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
override NoteHead.style = #'cross
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

b4-.
 f-- b-.
 b |b}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

lyr = 
\backslash
lyricmode { BAN HORNS UP! 
\backslash
markup 
\backslash
bold AND 
\backslash
markup 
\backslash
bold UP! }
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

