\begin_layout Section
Adding Movement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once the band has learned the basics, it is now possible to teach skills
 that involve more complex motions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Mark Time
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The band can 
\noun on
Mark Time 
\noun default
while in place to establish a maintenance of rhythm.
 It can also be visually appealing if the entire band is in sync and marking
 time all at the same time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Marking Time
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Marking time involves one main motion: the bending of the knee.
 This motion will happen to both legs.
 This is demonstrated in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand vref
reference "fig:mark-time"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The toes of the foot are to remain planted on the ground, from the very
 end of the toe, to just before the arch of the foot.
 The heel of the foot is to raise up and be above the ground about the diameter
 of a tennis ball (30⁰).
 The knee should bend outwards from its position, already unlocked and slightly
 bent.
 Everything from the waist up should remain absolutely motionless.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
To mark time, alternate moving the leg to this position and back to normal
 Attention leg.
 As you move your left foot down, raise your right foot, effectively alternating
 between each leg.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The most important aspect of marking time is keeping your upper body motionless.
 If you were to imagine having a glass of water resting on the top of your
 head, you would not want to spill any of the water out of the glass.
 To do this, engage your core and maintain stability in your upper body.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To mark time 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

in time,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 you will alternate your feet to the beat.
 Your left foot will always raise on beats 2 & 4, and your right foot will
 always raise on 1 & 3.
 You can also think of this as lowering your left foot on beats 1 & 3 and
 lowering your right foot on beats 2 & 4.
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename pose_graphics/marktime.svg
	lyxscale 25
	scale 20

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:mark-time"

\end_inset

The raised leg position in a proper mark time.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Starting and Stopping a Mark Time
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The band starts marking time when a leader shouts:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
MARK TIME MARK!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The timing of the syllables forms three even quarter notes of a 4/4 measure,
 landing on beats 1–3.
 The band shall then respond and begin marking time by raising the left
 foot:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
AND!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The band's response shall land on beat 4 of the measure.
 Once the band has lifted the left foot, this is treated like a pickup measure
 to the mark time.
 The band shall remain marking time, and on beat 4 of each measure, shout
 the measure number multiplied by 4 (or simply, the current net beat number):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
(1) (2) (3) FOUR! (5) (6) (7) EIGHT! (...)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This pattern will repeat indefinitely.
 If a mark time is interrupted by another maneuver or command, the count
 resets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Flex LilyPond
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

rhythm = 
\backslash
relative c'' {
\backslash
time 4/4
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
override NoteHead.style = #'cross
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

b4-.
 f-- b-.
 b |r2 r4 b |r2 r4 b}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

lyr = 
\backslash
