\begin_layout Subsubsection
About Turn
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An 
\noun on
About Turn 
\noun default
is a 180º rotation, rotating counterclockwise.
 The band begins an About Turn when a leader shouts:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
A 'BOUT TURN HO!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The timing of the syllables forms three even quarter notes of a 4/4 measure,
 landing on beats 1–3, with a sixteenth appoggiatura before beat 1.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The band does not do anything on beat 4 of this measure.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
On beat 1 of the next measure, the left foot is moved to be rotated 90º
 to the left.
 The left foot should pivot around the heel.
 The upper body should begin rotation, but will not rotate greater than
 90º CCW until beat 4.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
On beat 2, the right foot rotates about the heel to match the orientation
 of the left foot.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
On beat 3, the left foot rotates another 90º to the left, resulting in a
 net rotation of 180º.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
On beat 4, the right foot rotates another 90º to the left, matching the
 orientation of the left foot.
 The upper body quickly rotates 90º to the left to match the direction of
 the feet.
 The band finally responds on beat 4:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
LOCK!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Flex LilyPond
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

rhythm = 
\backslash
relative c'' {
\backslash
time 4/4
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
override NoteHead.style = #'cross
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
partial 16 b16| b4-.
 f-- b-- r | r2 r4 b4->}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

lyr = 
\backslash
lyricmode { A- BOUT TURN HO! 
\backslash
markup 
\backslash
bold LOCK! }
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

<<   
\backslash
new Voice = melody 
\backslash
rhythm   
\backslash
new Lyrics 
\backslash
lyricsto melody 
\backslash
lyr >>
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Facings
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\noun on
Facings 
\noun default
are only typically used in fundamental block.
 They allow the band to be rotated very quickly.
 They are similar to Flankings, which are much more common.
 Facings only occur with a given command:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
BAN [LEF/RIGHT] HASTE!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The timing of the syllables forms three even quarter notes of a 4/4 measure,
 landing on beats 1–3.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
On beat 4, the band then will then rotate by pivoting on both feet and rotating
 the upper body.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
If the band is Facing to the left, the band will pivot on the heel of the
 left foot and the ball of the right.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If the band is Facing to the right, the band will pivot on the heel of the
 right foot and the ball of the left.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
This rotation is quick and snappy as the upper body rotates at the same
 time as well.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
On beat 1 of the next measure, the foot that is backwards of the other moves
 forward to match the position of the other.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The band responds with:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
HUN TWO!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The response begins on beat 4 as the feet pivot, then ends on beat 1 as
 the feet come together.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Flex LilyPond
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

rhythm = 
\backslash
relative c'' {
\backslash
time 4/4
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
override NoteHead.style = #'cross
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

b4-.
 f-- b-.
 b | b}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

lyr = 
\backslash
lyricmode { BAN LEF HASTE! 
\backslash
markup 
\backslash
bold HUN 
\backslash
markup 
\backslash
bold TWO! }
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

<<   
\backslash
new Voice = melody 
\backslash
rhythm   
\backslash
new Lyrics 
\backslash
lyricsto melody 
\backslash
lyr >>
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Moving to new places
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All of the previous fundamentals only take place in one spot.
 Now, we discuss basic traveling skills.
 Note that the following fundamentals are not directly given via commands,
 but are given through a set of instructions (e.g., 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

mark time 4, forwards march 4
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This also introduces 
\emph on
instruction giving
\emph default
, contrary to command giving.
 When command giving, the band immediately responds and does an action when
 a command is given.
 In instruction giving, the band is given a series of commands, given time
 to process them mentally, then the band is given a command to begin.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
When I say 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

instruction giving,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 I'm referring to delivering a set of maneuvers for the band to perform
 (e.g., 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

mark time 8, forwards march 8, and close
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) instead of more generic commands (e.g., 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

16 beats to go back to set 1
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\end_inset

 So, instruction giving is appended by a command.
 When the band has been given instructions, the leader will shout to start
 the instructions given:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
HUP HUP RIGHT NOW!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The timing of the syllables forms four even quarter notes of a 4/4 measure,
 landing on beats 1–4.
 Depending on what the band's first move is, they will have a different
 response, but will always give back a response.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Flex LilyPond
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

rhythm = 
\backslash
relative c'' {
\backslash
time 4/4
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
override NoteHead.style = #'cross
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

b4-.
 b-.
 b-.
 b-.}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

lyr = 
\backslash
lyricmode { HUP HUP RIGHT NOW! }
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

<<   
\backslash
new Voice = melody 
\backslash
rhythm   
\backslash
new Lyrics 
\backslash
lyricsto melody 
\backslash
lyr >>
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Lock-Push
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\noun on
Lock-Push
\noun default
 begins movement by allowing a stationary performer to begin traveling forwards.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The band Lock-Prep-Steps when going backwards.
 See Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand vref
reference "subsec:Backwards-March"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for details.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The Lock-Push is colloquially called the 
\noun on
Step-Off
\noun default
.
\begin_inset VSpace defskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
The Lock-Push is comprised of two separate parts: the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lock
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

push.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 This is demonstrated in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand vref
reference "fig:lock-push"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
On the first beat, the feet need to be together at the standard Attention
 pose.
 The performer will be stationary at this point, so the only action necessary
 is if the performer is marking time (which they will then just Lock and
 Close).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
On the second beat, the left foot will extend outwards 22.5 inches
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
As denoted later, various step sizes exist and this description implies
 an 8:5 step size.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and only the heel of the foot will touch the ground.
 It is important to note that the toes of the left foot should be raised
 upwards.
 The right foot will begin to roll up onto the ball.
 It is important to keep the upper body stabilized (the left foot should
 touch, not pound or punch the ground).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Always start with the left foot!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\noindent
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename pose_graphics/lockpush.svg
	lyxscale 25
	scale 20

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:lock-push"

\end_inset

A proper step off, where the left heel is 22.5 inches in front of its initial
 position.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
The band shouts when doing a Lock-Push:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
LOCK PUSH!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The response is two even quarter notes.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
No sheet music because it could land anywhere in the measure (e.g., 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

MT2, FM8
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace defskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Tips for learning a good Lock-Push:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Imagine there is a sticky note on the bottom of your foot that says 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Hi Mom!
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 In order for your mom to see the note from the stadium seats, you have
 to raise your toes as high as possible so she can see the note.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After performing the Step-Off, you will move directly into a continued Roll
 Step!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Roll Step
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\noun on
Roll Step 
\noun default
is the most rudimentary and fundamental way to travel the field.
 It allows the band to move with a standardized look.
 This section will focus on an 8:5 (8 steps for every 5 yards) step size.
 It is common to call the culmination of roll stepping and other maneuvers
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

marching.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace defskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "step-size"

\end_inset

Once you have initiated a Step-Off and your left foot is in front of you,
 roll through the entire left foot as you pickup your right foot and place
 it 22.5 inches in front of your left foot, only placing down the heel.
 Then as you roll through your entire right foot, pickup your left foot
 and place the heel 22.5 inches in front of your right foot.
 Alternate feet and you are Roll Stepping! It's like walking, but rolling
 through each step at a fixed distance with no upper body movement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We march with step sizes of 22.5 inches, because 8 of these specifically
 defined steps will allow you to travel exactly 5 yards.
 We can also march with different step sizes.
 See Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand vref
reference "subsec:adjusted-marching-responses"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for more details.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Important things to remember:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The entire upper body shall remain 
\series bold
motionless
\series default
 throughout the Step Off and Roll Stepping.
 Your core will need to be engaged to maintain this stability.
 Squeeze your glutes.
 Imagine there is a glass of water on your head and you can't spill any
 of it.
 You should not move your upper body at all!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Rolling through each foot is important for maintaining stability.
 Imagine there is a tube of toothpaste on the ground and you have to use
 your entire foot to squeeze it out from back to front.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The height of your toes must remain as high as possible, just like in the
 step-off.
 This will help you with the rolling action.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Why should we keep our upper body still?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is vital that your upper body remain motionless while marching because
 you are also playing an instrument while doing this! Imagine if you were
 to march a show while bouncing up and down, your tone would go up and down
 too! Multiply that by 100 people in the band and now we can't agree that
 A4 = 440 Hz.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Guiding
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\noun on
Guiding 
\noun default
is one of the most important fundamentals to execute, since it allows the
 band to appear uniform.
 The idea of guiding is to keep forms straight.
 For example, when in fundamental block, you are in a row with everyone
 else in your section, and it is not going to look good if everyone is slightly
 offset from each other.
 Instead of a straight line, we have a wavy line!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The way to fix this is to guide.
 By guiding, you keep your body in line with the person on your right.
 You will always guide to the person on your right.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
There are exceptions to this but they are less common.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 If you are in a form where there are also people in front of you, you will
 also guide forwards, making sure you are in line with the person to your
 right and the person in front of you.
 Imagine keeping your shoulders on an imaginary axis that is perfectly in
 line with your guides.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Responses in Fundamental Block
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When marching in fundamental block, the band will shout responses when hitting
 subdivisions of marching lengths.
 The response varies depending on the direction of travel:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
When traveling parallel to the sideline
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Half way between yard lines (when the right foot is placed down):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
HALF!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
On the yard line (when the right foot is placed down):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
HIT!
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
When traveling perpendicular to the sideline
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Every fourth step, the beat number:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
FOUR! EIGHT! [...]
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
Marching an 8:5 parallel to sideline for 10 yards:
\end_layout

