\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
Different responses vary depending on the step size.
 See Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand vref
reference "subsec:adjusted-marching-responses"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for responses with different step sizes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Lock and Close
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Lock-and-Close"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the band ends its maneuvers, they will 
\noun on
Lock and Close
\noun default
.
 The Lock and Close will always end a maneuver and put the performers feet
 idle and stationary.
 It consists of two parts: the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lock
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

close.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lock
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 occurs with the right foot and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

locks
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the foot in place.
 For example, after roll stepping, the right foot will lock down in place
 where the performer will stand after marching.
 After marking time, the right foot locks down on the ground and does not
 lift back up.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

close
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 occurs with the left foot and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

closes
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the feet together.
 The left foot will lock next to the right foot to close the distance between
 the feet.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The response forms three even eighth notes:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
LOCK AND CLOSE!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The response begins on the lock of the right foot and ends with the close
 of the left foot.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Changing Directions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now that we can move forwards, mark time, and start and stop, let's find
 out how to move backwards.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Backwards March
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Backwards-March"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\noun on
Backwards March
\noun default
 allows performers to move backwards, unlike roll step which is forwards.
 A different technique is used for marching backwards.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As it was important for rolling through each step for a forwards march,
 it is important to remain on the balls of your feet for a backwards march.
 Backwards march is colloquially called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

drag toes
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 since that is what the technique entails.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
When marching backwards, always be on the balls of your feet.
 Your heels should not touch the ground in any capacity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Bend your knees slightly more than the unlocked position for attention to
 absorb some shock from dragging your toes on the ground.
 Your upper body should not move at all, just like a roll step.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
As you move your feet back for each step, imagine tickling the blades of
 the grass on the ground: your feet should have contact with the ground,
 but not be so forceful as to inhibit movement.
 If you were backwards marching in sand, there would be two, straight, parallel
 lines in the sand where your toes dragged.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The band does a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Lock Prep Step
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 when beginning a backwards march, similar to the Lock-Push when forwards
 marching (this is demonstrated in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand vref
reference "fig:lock-prep-step"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
LOCK PREP STEP!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename pose_graphics/prep_step.svg
	lyxscale 20
	scale 20

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:lock-prep-step"

\end_inset

The proper 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Lock Prep Step
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 movement, as notated.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The response forms three even quarter notes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Rock and Roll
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\noun on
Rock and Roll 
\noun default
allows performers to switch from going forwards to backwards, or going from
 backwards to forwards, without stopping.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
To switch to going backwards from marching forwards, at the time of the
 rock and roll, the right foot will be placed down like a normal roll step.
 However, when the foot is placed down, the weight of the body is going
 to roll through the foot and move to the ball of the foot, then the left
 foot is raised to be on the balls, effectively placing the performer in
 a perfect backwards march position.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
It is important to roll all the way through the right foot.
 You can imagine an imaginary pane of Plexiglas positioned vertically at
 the point where you want to rock and roll: roll all the way through the
 right foot so you can kiss the pane of glass.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Once rolled through the right foot, it is necessary to not linger in this
 position, and immediately begin moving backwards to regain momentum.
 However, it is important that the full weight of the body rolls through
 the right foot and moves forwards as much as possible.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
To switch to going forwards from marching backwards, at the time of the
 rock and roll, the right foot will be placed down like a normal drag toes
 step.
 However, when the foot is placed down, the weight of the body is going
 to roll through the foot and move to the heel of the foot, the the left
 foot is lowered to be on the heel, effectively placing the performer in
 a perfect roll step position.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
It is important that the full weight of the body move back as far as possible,
 then begins moving forwards to gain momentum and begin a forwards march.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
The band shouts when doing a rock and roll:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
ROCK AND ROLL!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The response forms two eighth notes, followed by a quarter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Flankings
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\noun on
Flankings 
\noun default
rotate performers from moving in one direction to another, but unlike Slow
 Turns, Flankings only need one beat to turn and happen while roll stepping,
 or when ending a roll step.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Flanking Left
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When performing a left flank, the body will quickly pivot on the ball of
 the right foot and on the heel of the left foot.
 The foot anchorage and rotation is exactly the same as a Facing.
 The rotation of the body will occur on the upbeat of the beat (the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of the beat).
 The upper body should rotate quickly and snappy.
 Typically, the Flank will be 90 degrees, but it is possible to only rotate
 partially to achieve a shorter rotation angle.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Flanking Right
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The procedure for flanking right is similar to flanking left, except an
 added 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

cheat step
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is used.
 The right foot, when flanking, should be placed on the ground half way
 of the total expected rotation.
 This will help with an easier body rotation snap.
 When flanking, the left foot will not be pivoted on, but will rather be
 swung around the be placed for the left foot step.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace defskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
The band shouts when doing a hip flank:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
AND ONE!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The response forms two eighth notes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Final Steps
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These fundamentals are the final icing on the cake and allow performers
 to move themselves in any direction or fashion on the field.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Traversing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\noun on
Traversing
\noun default
 is marching one direction while having the upper body face a different
 direction, up to 90º left or right.
 It is common to 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

traverse home
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 to allow the band to march one direction and point the instruments towards
 the home sideline for best audio quality.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Traversing involves rotating the upper body so that it is facing one direction,
 while marching in another.
 Therefore, it is important to traverse correctly to reduce the amount of
 strain and tension caused on the spine.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Traversing involves two directions: the 
\emph on
march direction
\emph default
, and the 
\emph on
facing direction
\emph default
.
 The march direction is the direction the performer is marching.
 This could be forwards, backwards, or any angle in between.
 The facing direction is the direction the upper body is facing while marching.
 It is possible for the facing direction to be anywhere within the range
 of –90º to +90º from the direction of the marching direction.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "traversing-never-backwards-at-90"

\end_inset

It should be noted that performers will never march backwards when the facing
 angle is 90º of the marching angle (they will forwards march instead).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
To rotate the body to the desired facing direction, the hips should rotate
 half way to the desired angle, then the upper torso should rotate another
 half, resulting in the shoulders above having a net rotation of the desired
 facing rotation.
 For example, if you needed to traverse 90º, your hips will rotate 45º,
 and the upper body will rotate another 45º, resulting in a 90º rotation
 of the upper body.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
To healthily rotate the upper body, imagine pushing the should behind forwards,
 instead of pulling the forwards shoulder back.
 It is also important to retain a proper posture and provide lower back
 support to reduce strain and soreness.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Beginners will experience that they will 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

drift
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or march oblique to their intended marching path if they are traversing.
 It is simple as just practicing to overcome this habit and remain on track.
 Extra attention must be given to the feet to achieve this.
 It may be helpful to overcompensate when first learning traversing to effective
ly remain the correct path.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Hip Switch
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Performers perform a 
\noun on
Hip Switch
\noun default
 (also known by its response 
\noun on
To the Rear) 
\noun default
when alternating from forwards marching to backwards marching (and vice
 versa) without changing velocity (heading in same direction).
 An example of when this may be used is traverse marching in a circle.
 If the performer must always face towards the home sideline and march in
 a circle, they will have to hip switch on either side of the circle so
 that they can remain marching in the correct direction without turning
 the upper body more than 90º.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The hip switch can be thought of as a 180º flank.
 When doing a hip switch, you will always pivot on your right foot, and
 your left foot will swing around.
 The movement, like all others, is short and snappy.
 After bringing the left foot around, it will either go directly into a
 roll step position or drag toes position, depending on the orientation
 the performer is about to march.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
The band shouts when doing a hip switch:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quote
TO THE REAR!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The response forms two eighth notes, followed by a quarter.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Adjusted Step Size
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A performer's step size will not always be a perfect 8:5 (8 steps every
 5 yards).
 Certain forms in the show's chart may have performers moving at a different
 speed (by changing step size, the performer's speed is inherently changed
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Given the performer remains in normal step time (does not move to half time
 or double time) and the tempo is constant, etc.
\end_layout

\end_inset

).
 To account for this, performers will have to march with an 
\noun on
Adjusted Step Size
\noun default
.
 This means that the distance in between each step will change.
 In an 8:5, the step distance is 22.5 in.
 For a 16:5 (16 steps for every 5 yards), the step distance is 11.25 in.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To adjust from marching in one step size to another, simply begin taking
 smaller/larger steps at the time of adjustment to begin marching at the
 new step size.
\end_layout

