\begin_layout Section
Making Shapes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Box
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A good way to practice flankings and roll stepping is with a 
\noun on
Box
\noun default
.
 A box consists of three turns, and can be in variable size and direction.
 For example, some valid boxes:
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Boxes in fundamental block will always be square and have an even side length.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
BoxL4 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Box Left 4
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 — Box with left turns, each side is 4 steps long
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
BoxR8 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Box Right 8
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 — Box with right turns, each side is 8 steps long
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the example of a BoxR8 (pronounced 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Box Right 8
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 This means that the band will take right turns, and march for 8 steps on
 each side before turning.
 The band will lock-push
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
If the band begins this box command from a non-stationary position (e.g.,
 marching, another box, etc.), the band will not stop and immediately begin
 the maneuvers for this box.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

and begin marching forwards for 8 steps.
 After 8 steps, the band will Flank right, and take another 8 steps.
 The band will Flank right again and take 8 more steps.
 Finally, the band will flank right again and take 8 more steps.
 The last step before finishing the box is a cheat step.
 The band finishes in the same direction as they started, so, the very last
 step is a flank to rotate back to the initial direction.
 The cheat step helps achieve this.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the box had a length of 4 instead of 8, simply only take 4 steps instead
 of 8.
 If the box was 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

left,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 simply take left flanks instead of right flanks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Traverse Box
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Boxes are good for practicing flankings and roll stepping.
 While we practice those fundamentals, we can also practice traversing with
 
\noun on
Traverse Boxes
\noun default
.
 Traverse boxes are just normal boxes, while also traversing in one direction
 the whole time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The traverse direction is chosen arbitrarily, as long as the direction can
 be traversed to at the beginning (cannot traverse home sideline when facing
 away).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One side of the traverse box will be backwards marching, one side will be
 forwards marching, and two sides will be traversing.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
As mentioned in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand vref
reference "traversing-never-backwards-at-90"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, performers will never march backwards when traversing at a 90º.
 They will forwards march while traversing the appropriate direction.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, if the band was facing field left, traversing to the home sideline,
 and doing a traverse box left:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The first edge of the box will be a forwards march while traversing home
 (upper body rotated right).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The band will then backwards flank and march backwards the second edge of
 the box.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The third edge of the box will be a forwards march while traversing home
 (upper body rotated left).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The final edge of the box will be a forwards march.
 The final step will return the feet to the initial direction ending the
 traverse box.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Adjusted Boxes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Just like how traverse boxes are good for practicing traversing, having
 boxes at adjusted step sizes can help with practicing adjusted steps.
 It is also fun to have the band do a box at one step size, then immediately
 have the band do another box at a different step size.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Examples of how adjusted boxes are labeled:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
BoxR6@6:5 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Box Right 6 at a 6:5
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring 00.00.0000
RoxL18@12:5 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Box Left 18 at a 12:5
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Conclusion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Congrats! If you are able to perform all the above fundamentals at any given
 tempo while playing your instrument, consider yourself an experienced marcher!
 The entire band should be able to execute all fundamentals while playing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Blocks
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This chapter will cover the technicalities and details of the several blocks
 the band forms, including Fundamental Block and Parade Block.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Fundamental Block
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\noun on
Fundamental Block
\noun default
 is used to group all the members of the band together on the field.
 The purpose of Fundamental Block is to allow for the teaching and practicing
 of fundamentals.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Layout
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The band has mostly kept sections in the same place from year to year.
 The general layout is found in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand vref
reference "fig:fundamental-block-general-layout"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename graphics/fundamental_block_layout.svg
	lyxscale 30
	scale 18

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:fundamental-block-general-layout"

\end_inset

The general layout of Fundamental Block.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each section begins consists of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

lines.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 A line is a row of performers that begins on the home sideline and extends
 towards the home hash (or further).
 A section leader or other veteran should be the one marching on the sideline,
 so that the general accuracy of the line is maximized.
 For each performer in each line, there is typically 4 steps of distance
 in between (an orange tick).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Parade Block
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\noun on
Parade Block
\noun default
 is used to allow the band to move together in a standardized position.
 This position is commonly used to travel to a stadium, during Homecoming
 Parade, etc.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Layout
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways true
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename graphics/parade_block_layout.svg
	lyxscale 30
	width 100col%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:parade-block-general-layout"

\end_inset

The general layout of Parade Block.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The instruments in Parade Block are typically in the same sections from
 year to year.
 The general layout is found in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand vref
reference "fig:parade-block-general-layout"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Some things are to be noted:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The Figure only represents a general layout.
 Year to year, adjustments are made to preserve symmetry with variable section
 sizes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Tenor Saxes are often merged with Alto Saxes if the section is small enough
 to merge.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Squish
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Sometimes while in Parade Block, the band has to fit within a restricted
 width.
 Examples of this include doorways, sidewalks, etc.
 When 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

squished,
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 rows are divided and stacked, effectively making the parade longer, but
 more narrow.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Those near the front of the parade will be the first to know that the parade
 must squish.
 They commonly will yell 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

squish!
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and those behind them yell it subsequently, effectively sending the message
 to the very back of the parade.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Marching
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Most of the time while in Parade Block, the band will be marching in time
 because the cadence is playing (see Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand vref
reference "subsec:Cadences"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for more information).
 The band should march in time with the current song or cadence.
 Remember, even though we may not be on the field, this should still be
 a roll step to ensure a good playing quality.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Turns
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Turning in Parade Block requires special attention to maintain the form.
 Because the block consists of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

rows
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the whole row must maintain a row shape throughout the entire turn.
 To do this, special marching is done:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The individual on the inside will march the least distance while turning,
 while the individual on the outside of the turn will march the most? Why
 is this? Imagine each band member is marching on quarter circles (this
 is demonstrated in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand vref
reference "fig:parade-block-turn"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 Since the circle furthest away from the epicenter of the circle has a larger
 circumference, the member that follows that path must march proportionately
 further.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement h
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename graphics/parade_block_turn.svg
	scale 50

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:parade-block-turn"

\end_inset

Members on the inside of a turn in Parade Block have a shorter distance
 to march compared to those further away from the epicenter (star) of the
 turn.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Cadences"

\end_inset

Cadences
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While in Parade Block, there are several cadences that the band recites
 while marching.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Flashes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While in Parade Block, instruments are held a special way and are flashed
 during the cadences.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
Drum Majors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Chapter
\start_of_appendix
Drill Repository
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These drills are available to use for practicing certain fundamentals.
 Presented are both computer generated drills, and some specially designed
 drills.
 The goal of the computer generated drills is to allow drum majors to present
 new content to the band, having an available resource at hand on the field.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here are the definitions for abbreviations used in these drills:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset VSpace defskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

